{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Kh538aSDrCVubB3pH5Ehg4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The first two tests with collects are failing because steps \"a\" and \"b\" are both entry points but only \"a\" is set as EntryStep, making \"b\" orphaned. I need to fix the test setup - the fanout pattern needs \"a\" to fan out to both \"b\" which then feeds into \"c\" via collect. Let me restructure.\n\nActually, the issue is that in the DifferentKeys and SameKey tests, I have steps a, b, c where a is entry. But b is not reachable from a - a goes to c, and b goes to c, but nothing goes to b.\n\nI need a to fan out to both b and c... wait no. Let me think about this differently. The test wants two wires targeting the same step (c) from different source steps (a and b). So a needs to reach b somehow, or both a and b need to be reachable.\n \nI'll restructure with a single entry point \"start\" that fans out to both \"a\" and \"b\", then route \"a\" to \"c\" with one output key and \"b\" to \"c\" with a different output key, collecting both results. Looking at how the existing fanout test structures its wires, I can model mine the same way: have the entry step fan out to two parallel steps, each with their own output mapping going into the collect step, then converge at the final step. Wait, so validation just needs every result wired somehow—either through an explicit Wire or via a Collect condition—and both can apply to the same result without conflict. That simplifies things. Let me restructure this by making \"a\" the source that fans out to multiple destinations.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":989,"cache_read_input_tokens":25401,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":989},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"